The paper deals with graph sparsification, which is a topic in both theoretical computer science and numerical analysis. The use of Laplacian matrices and quadratic forms suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.DS (data structures and algorithms) or cs.NA (numerical analysis) sub-categories. The paper also mentions graph partitioning, which is a topic in cs.CG (computational geometry) and cs.SI (social and information networks). Finally, the use of spectral similarity and conductance suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.LG (machine learning) sub-category.
